abstract: Diners are returning from their summer vacations and heading back into restaurants.
snippet: Diners are returning from their summer vacations and heading back into restaurants.
lead_paragraph: Restaurants scrapped printed menus and told diners to scan QR codes. Plexiglass partitions were installed between tables. Restaurants began selling more merchandise and even kitchen goods.

abstract: The Russian president’s remarks were his first about Saturday’s explosion on the Kerch Strait Bridge.
snippet: The Russian president’s remarks were his first about Saturday’s explosion on the Kerch Strait Bridge.
lead_paragraph: President Vladimir V. Putin on Sunday accused Ukraine of being behind the attack on the bridge linking Crimea to Russia, calling it an act of terrorism.

main: Putin blames Ukraine for the Crimea bridge blast.

abstract: Twin explosions were the deadliest terrorist attack in the country in five years and underscored the growing threat posed by the terrorist group Al Shabab.
snippet: Twin explosions were the deadliest terrorist attack in the country in five years and underscored the growing threat posed by the terrorist group Al Shabab.
lead_paragraph: MOGADISHU, Somalia — The students, pondering their next moves in life, lined up at the Ministry of Education to collect their high school certificates. Nearby on the bustling street, patrons packed restaurants and shops, while vendors, including mothers with children on their laps, sold vegetables and exchanged money. And just up the road, old men trickled out of a mosque before crowding into buses and three-wheeled tuk-tuks.

main: ‘Indescribable’: Somalis Recount Horror of Blasts That Killed at Least 100
print_headline: Somalis Describe Horror of Twin Blasts

abstract: A Ukrainian colonel said attacks that took out howitzers and armored vehicles were carried out by Iranian-made drones that had not previously been used outside of the Middle East.
snippet: A Ukrainian colonel said attacks that took out howitzers and armored vehicles were carried out by Iranian-made drones that had not previously been used outside of the Middle East.
lead_paragraph: KOROPOVE, Ukraine — A new and, Ukrainian officers say, frighteningly effective weapon has appeared in the war on the Russian side: Iranian-made attack drones.

main: Russia Deploys Iranian Attack Drones, Ukrainian Military Says

abstract: Yevgeny V. Prigozhin, the founder of the private military group, dismissed a report from The Washington Post saying that leaked intelligence showed he had offered to share Russian Army positions with Ukraine.
snippet: Yevgeny V. Prigozhin, the founder of the private military group, dismissed a report from The Washington Post saying that leaked intelligence showed he had offered to share Russian Army positions with Ukraine.
lead_paragraph: The head of the Wagner private military group on Monday rejected a report that he had offered to share with Ukraine the positioning of Russian Army troops around Bakhmut, in eastern Ukraine, in exchange for a withdrawal of Kyiv’s forces from the area.

main: The Wagner leader disputes a report that he offered to betray Russia.

abstract: President Biden has quickly backed demonstrators in Iran. When the country faced similar unrest 13 years ago, U.S. officials feared such a strong approach would be counterproductive.
snippet: President Biden has quickly backed demonstrators in Iran. When the country faced similar unrest 13 years ago, U.S. officials feared such a strong approach would be counterproductive.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The last time waves of protests swept Iran, after the killing of a young woman who was standing on the sidelines of an anti-government rally in 2009, Barack Obama hesitated to back the anti-government movement publicly for fear that Tehran would claim the C.I.A. was secretly sparking the unrest.

main: Biden’s Support for Iran Protesters Comes After Bitter Lessons of 2009
print_headline: As Revolt Rises in Iran, U.S. Takes Different Tack

lead_paragraph: ZAPORIZHZHIA, Ukraine — The main front in Russia’s military onslaught on Ukraine appears to have shifted dangerously to the south of the country, risking a catastrophe at Europe’s largest nuclear power plant and setting up a possible make-or-break struggle for an important regional capital seized by Russia at the start of its invasion.

main: Threat to Ukraine Nuclear Plant Increases as Fighting Rages
